Comment: Chemical entities which represent real physical molecules.
A chemical formula that indicates the relative number of each constituting chemical element of a species or molecular entity.
A combined representation of a number indicating the amount of an element in a species and the element.
An atom or isotope.
The address of a web page that describes a resource.
A relation between a species or molecular entity and the chemical formula describing the relative number of each constituting chemical element of the species or molecular entity.
A relation that defines that a species or molecular entity contains a chemical element.
A relation that defines a combined representation of a number indicating the amount of an element in a species and the element.
A relation that defines the number of atoms of a given element contained in a species or molecular entity.
A number that indicates the amount of an element in a species.
The combined masses of all atoms of a molecule. In ChEBI, http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/chebi/mass is defined as an annotation property.
An identifier designed to codify chemical species, molecules or substances. In ChEBI, http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/chebi/inchi is defined as an annotation property.
A fixed-length representation of InChI. In ChEBI, http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/chebi/inchikey is defined as an annotation property.

A numerical identifier designed to uniquely identify all chemical substances. Also in PeriodicTable, http://www.daml.org/2003/01/periodictable/PeriodicTable#casRegistryID is defined as a data type property.
An alternative name of a chemical species, molecule or substance.
The date when a web page was accessed.
The value of a property. Also in OntoCAPE, http://www.theworldavatar.com/ontology/ontocape/upper_level/system.owl#value is designed as a data type property.
The amount of energy required to raise the temperature of 1 mole of a substance in the gas-phase by 1K.

Source: Constant Pressure Heat Capacity of Gas
Comment: The amount of energy required to raise the temperature of 1 mole of a substance in the gas-phase by 1K at constant pressure [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Constant Pressure Heat Capacity of Liquid
Comment: The amount of energy required to raise the temperature of 1 mole of a substance in the liquid-phase by 1K at constant pressure [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Constant Pressure Heat Capacity of Solid
Comment: The amount of energy required to raise the temperature of 1 mole of a substance in the solid-phase by 1K at constant pressure [Chemistry LibreTexts].
The lowest energy which must be supplied to the parent molecule to cause it to produce a particular specified ion [EVISA].
The minimum energy required to remove an electron from an atom or molecule in order to produce a positive ion [EVISA].
The minimum pressure needed to liquefy a substance at the critical temperature [Chemistry LibreTexts].
A measure of how much the energy of atoms and molecules becomes more spread out in a process in the liquid phase [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Entropy of Liquid At Standard Conditions

Comment: A measure of how much the energy of atoms and molecules becomes more spread out in a process in the solid phase [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Entropy Of Solid At Standard Conditions
Entropy Of Solid At Standard Conditions (1 bar)
Target: Entropy Of Solid At Standard Conditions

Comment: A measure of the average amount of energy of motion, or kinetic energy, a system contains [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Temperature at which the pressure exerted by the surroundings upon a liquid is equalled by the pressure exerted by the vapour of the liquid; under this condition, addition of heat results in the transformation of the liquid into its vapour without raising the temperature [Encyclopedia of Britanica].
The highest temperature at which a substance can exist as a liquid [Chemistry LibreTexts] or the maximum temperature at which a gas can be liquefied by pressure [Encyclopedia of Britannica].
The temperature at which a solid changes into a liquid [Chemistry LibreTexts].
The state where both the temperature and pressure of the three phases of a substance coexist in equilibrium [Chemistry LibreTexts].
The volume of a fixed mass of fluid at the critical temperature and pressure [Chemistry Glossary].

kH(T) = k°H exp(d(ln(kH))/d(1/T) ((1/T) - 1/(298.15 K))) Henry’s law says that the solubility of a gas in a liquid is directly proportional to the partial pressure of the gas above the liquid: C = kPgas [Chemistry LibreTexts].
The enthalpy change for a reaction in which exactly 1 mole of a pure substance is formed from free elements in their most stable states under standard state conditions.

Source: Enthalpy Of Combustion Of Liquid At Standard Conditions
Comment: The enthalpy change when 1 mole of a liquid substance burns (combines vigorously with oxygen) under standard state conditions; it is sometimes called “heat of combustion” [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Enthalpy Of Formation Of Gas At Standard Conditions
Comment: The enthalpy change when 1 mole of a gaseous substance forms from its constituting elements under standard state conditions.

Source: Enthalpy Of Formation Of Liquid At Standard Conditions
Comment: The enthalpy change when 1 mole of a liquid substance forms from its constituting elements under standard state conditions.

Source: Enthalpy Of Reaction At Standard Conditions
Comment: The difference in enthalpy between products and reactants under standard state conditions [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Enthalpy Of Sublimation At Standard Conditions
Comment: The energy that must be supplied as heat per mole of molecules converted to vapor from a solid [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Enthalpy Of Vaporization At Standard Conditions
Comment: The energy that must be supplied as heat per mole of molecules vaporized from a liquid [Chemistry LibreTexts].

Source: Free Energy Of Reaction At Standard Conditions
Comment: The energy associated with a chemical reaction that can be used to do work. The free energy of a system is the sum of its enthalpy (H) plus the product of the temperature (Kelvin) and the entropy (S) of the system [Chem.Tamu].
The density of a substance at the critical point.
